 Items such as soap, skin creams are likely to be purchased in bulk in large
 families.
 Since the frequency of purchases would be lower when the quantity of bulk
 purchases increases- this may cause us to overestimate consumption significantl
y.
 One way to adjust the quantity consumed is by estimating the storage using
 the number of rooms as a proxy of storage space.
 However, the store and consume consumption pattern does not require plenty
 of storage space and may not depend on the number of rooms as such.
 Another way to test for store-and-consumption pattern is testing the closest
 market from the household.
 The data for distance from market (or the cost of public transport) is
 quite sparse (a lot of NAs - which could be because the market as described
 in the survey is never visited or that it doesn't exist in the immediate
 region).
 Assuming that the habit of stocking is uniform throughout the country (this
 may sound a sweeping assumption - but since we do take region into account
 - we should be able to account regional differences), we can find household
 factors (e.g.
 household size or distance from market) that may affect consumption.
